Analyzing RNA-seq data with DESeq2

Teunis, Marc A.T (Adapted after Michael I. Love, Simon Anders, and Wolfgang Huber)

05/22/2020

Abstract

A basic task in the analysis of count data from RNA-seq is the detection of differentially expressed genes. The count data are presented as a table which reports, for each sample, the number of sequence fragments that have been assigned to each gene. Analogous data also arise for other assay types, including comparative ChIP-Seq, HiC, shRNA screening, mass spectrometry. An important analysis question is the quantification and statistical inference of systematic changes between conditions, as compared to within-condition variability. The package DESeq2 provides methods to test for differential expression by use of negative binomial generalized linear models; the estimates of dispersion and logarithmic fold changes incorporate data-driven prior distributions This vignette explains the use of the package and demonstrates typical workflows. An RNA-seq workflow on the Bioconductor website covers similar material to this vignette but at a slower pace, including the generation of count matrices from FASTQ files. DESeq2 package version: 1.26.0

Standard workflow

Note: if you use DESeq2 in published research, please cite:

Love, M.I., Huber, W., Anders, S. (2014) Moderated estimation of fold change and dispersion for RNA-seq data with DESeq2. Genome Biology, 15:550. 10.1186/s13059-014-0550-8

Other Bioconductor packages with similar aims are edgeR, limma, DSS, EBSeq, and baySeq.

Quick start

Here we show the most basic steps for a differential expression analysis. There are a variety of steps upstream of DESeq2 that result in the generation of counts or estimated counts for each sample, which we will discuss in the sections below. This code chunk assumes that you have a count matrix called cts and a table of sample information called coldata. The design indicates how to model the samples, here, that we want to measure the effect of the condition, controlling for batch differences. The two factor variables batch and condition should be columns of coldata. The most easy startpoint to perform this analysis is if you have a SummarizedExperiment class object that stores all the neccessary data.

dds <- DESeqDataSetFromMatrix(countData = cts,
                              colData = coldata,
                              design= ~ batch + condition)
dds <- DESeq(dds)
resultsNames(dds) # lists the coefficients
res <- results(dds, name="condition_trt_vs_untrt")
# or to shrink log fold changes association with condition:
res <- lfcShrink(dds, coef="condition_trt_vs_untrt", type="apeglm")

The following assumptions are made:

  • We focus on transcriptomics analysis only in this lessons
  • We assume you have the raw RNAseq counts available in a matrix, where the columns are the sample ids and the rows are the genes from which the transcripts

Input data

Why un-normalized counts?

As input, the DESeq2 package expects count data as obtained, e.g., from RNA-seq or another high-throughput sequencing experiment, in the form of a matrix of integer values. The value in the i-th row and the j-th column of the matrix tells how many reads can be assigned to gene i in sample j. Analogously, for other types of assays, the rows of the matrix might correspond e.g.to binding regions (with ChIP-Seq) or peptide sequences (with quantitative mass spectrometry). We will list method for obtaining count matrices in sections below.

The values in the matrix should be un-normalized counts or estimated counts of sequencing reads (for single-end RNA-seq) or fragments (for paired-end RNA-seq). The RNA-seq workflow describes multiple techniques for preparing such count matrices. It is important to provide count matrices as input for DESeq2s statistical model [@Love2014] to hold, as only the count values allow assessing the measurement precision correctly. The DESeq2 model internally corrects for library size, so transformed or normalized values such as counts scaled by library size should not be used as input.

The DESeqDataSet

The object class used by the DESeq2 package to store the read counts and the intermediate estimated quantities during statistical analysis is the DESeqDataSet, which will usually be represented in the code here as an object dds.

A technical detail is that the DESeqDataSet class extends the (Ranged)SummarizedExperiment class of the SummarizedExperiment package. The Ranged part refers to the fact that the rows of the assay data (here, the counts) can be associated with genomic ranges (the exons of genes). This association facilitates downstream exploration of results, making use of other Bioconductor packages range-based functionality (e.g.find the closest ChIP-seq peaks to the differentially expressed genes).

A DESeqDataSet object must have an associated design formula. The design formula expresses the variables which will be used in modeling. The formula should be a tilde (~) followed by the variables with plus signs between them (it will be coerced into an formula if it is not already). The design can be changed later, however then all differential analysis steps should be repeated, as the design formula is used to estimate the dispersions and to estimate the log2 fold changes of the model.

Note: In order to benefit from the default settings of the package, you should put the variable of interest at the end of the formula and make sure the control level is the first level.

We will now show constructing a DESeqDataSet, depending on what pipeline was used upstream of DESeq2 to generated counts or estimated counts you could use another: see the DESeq2 vignette or RNAseq workflow on bioconductor for more details.

We will start from downloading a dataset from GEO with the GEOqeary packages (See lesson 4)

RNA-Seq data processing and analysis.

Quote from the article by Weger et al., 2016

Image analysis and base calling were performed using the Illumina pipeline (Real Time Analysis and Offline Base Caller 1.8). All raw sequence data are available from the GEO database (accession number GSE76073, http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/geo/). Reads were mapped onto the Zv9 assembly of the zebrafish genome using STAR 2.3.8 [35]. Uniquely mapped reads were counted for each gene locus as annotated in Ensembl v75 using the Python Package HTseq v0.5.3p1. Read counts were normalized using DESeq2 [36]. For downstream analysis a variance stabilizing transformation was applied to the normalized data [37].

Construct a SummarizedExperiment

The essential step here is that the columnames of the counts DataFrame should exactly match (in order and symantics) the rownames of the colData element.

If all the elements are in the right shape we can create a SummarizedExperiment with SummarizedExperiment()

To remind you of the relationships between the different elements of a formal class SummarizedExperiment R object:

These are the steps: 1. Set rownames of pheno_data and convert to class AnnotatedDataFrame(). Convert all factor variables to factors.1.Set rownames of feature_data and convert to AnnotatedDataFrame()1.Remove first column of counts, leave only count data1.Check if rownames(pheno_data) is equal to colnames(counts)1.Fix rownames and if neccessary1.create metadata (need to be a list)1. AddfeatureData1. Check the factor levels of the experimental predictors/grouping variables, and relevel if neccessary 1. From the individual parts create aSummarizedExperiment. Add the metadata. You can create the SummarizedExperiment from the ExpressionSet with the function:SummarizedExperiment()`

look at the help function for SummarizedExperiment() to learn what arguments should be passed in

?SummarizedExperiment

To complete these steps we will need tools from bioconductor packages, for example to access data stored in the ExpressionSet that we downloaded from GEO. The data wrangling that is needed to harmonize the colnames and the rownames can be done with tools from {tidyverse}.

It easier to create a new column in col_data_new on the basis of columns genotype_ch1, treatment_ch1 and zeitgeber_time_ch1. We have to first change the values, for these variables for it to match the keys in the colnames of cnts

names(col_data_new)
## [1] "title"              "geo_accession"      "genotype_ch1"      
## [4] "strain_ch1"         "treatment_ch1"      "zeitgeber_time_ch1"
col_data_new <- col_data_new %>%
  dplyr::mutate(
    genotype_ch1 = ifelse(
      genotype_ch1 == "Wild type", "WT", genotype_ch1),
    genotype_ch1 = ifelse(
      genotype_ch1 == "rx3 weak mutant", "WEAK", genotype_ch1),
    genotype_ch1 = ifelse(
      genotype_ch1 == "rx3 strong mutant", "RX3", genotype_ch1),
    ## we managed to come close, no change treatment
    treatment_ch1 = "DMSO" ## only a single value we need to change
    ## zeitgeber is already the good key

  ) %>%  
## now we create a new column
  unite(
    col = "sample_id",
    c("genotype_ch1",
      "treatment_ch1",
      "zeitgeber_time_ch1"),
    remove = FALSE,
    sep = "_"
    )

Match colnames of cnts with rownames of col_data_new

Steps:

  • First we select the proper columns from cnts that belong to the coldata,
  • We change the order of cnts columns to match the rows in col_data_new
  • than we check it all worked out
  • Finally we are ready to create our SummarizedExperiment, add some metadata just for kicks, and we can continue.

**You see, data cleaning and preparation indeed takes about 70-80% of your work. If only the people who are submitting the data knew more about the underlying principles!!

## set new rownames on col_data_new
rownames(col_data_new) <- col_data_new$sample_id
## check manually if this went well

## select columns of cnts that we have colData for
ind_col <- colnames(cnts) %in% rownames(col_data_new) ## should be length(cnts)

## we can remove column 21 'the gene length'
## let's put it in a featureData dataframe, together with the rownames of cnts as rownames for featureData
feature_data <- data.frame(
  gene_length = cnts$gene_length
)
rownames(feature_data) <- rownames(cnts)

## select the proper columns in cnts
cnts_new <- cnts[, ind_col]

Are we done?

To see if we are ready to create our SummarizedExperiment we check if the rownames of col_data_new match the colnames of cnts_new

colnames(cnts_new) == rownames(col_data_new)
##  [1] TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE

YES!! WE ARE DONE We are lucky that we do not have to change the column order of cnts_new If you are not so lucky: here is pointer on how to do this:

## let's reorder the order of col_data_new
col_data_dummy <- col_data_new[c(12:1), ]

col_data_dummy$sample_id == col_data_new$sample_id ## the order is reverse
##  [1] FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE
colnames(cnts_new) == rownames(col_data_dummy)
##  [1] FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE
## using the new order to rearrange the columns in cnts_new
cnts_dummy <- cnts_new %>%
  dplyr::select(
    col_data_dummy$sample_id
  )

Differential expression analysis

We use the DESeq2 package

Prepare analysis using the SummarizedExperiment object and the DESeqDataSet() function. We look at the effect of genotype_ch1 and zeitgeber_time_ch1 on the differential gene expression by passing in the formula

design = ~ genotype_ch1 + zeitgeber_time_ch1

ddsSE <- DESeq2::DESeqDataSet(sumexp, design = ~ genotype_ch1 + zeitgeber_time_ch1)
## Warning in DESeq2::DESeqDataSet(sumexp, design = ~genotype_ch1 +
## zeitgeber_time_ch1): some variables in design formula are characters, converting
## to factors

We can filter for low expression before analyzing further

Only genes with total row count sum of more than 10 are kept in the data.

keep <- rowSums(counts(ddsSE)) >= 10
ddsSE <- ddsSE[keep,]

Running the analysis with default settings

ddsDE <- DESeq(ddsSE)

Getting the result table

The results table is the table containing the end results of the analysis. This is what you should write to disk for future reference, along with the code that generated the table. Store them close together. Preferably you build an R-package around your analysis, containing all the components neccessary to reproduce the exact result. In the module Workflow that will be part of the bioinformatics courses from 2021 onwards, we will demonstrate how to build such an R package.

  1. The WT condition, for all zeitgeber_ch1 conditions vs the weak mutant condition WEAK, for all zeitgeber_ch1 conditions.
  2. The WT condition, for all zeitgeber_ch1 conditions vs the weak mutant condition RX3, for all zeitgeber_ch1 conditions.

Because there is only one condition per sample, and no replicates, we have to be careful on drawing strong statistical conclusions.

Log fold change shrinkage for visualization and ranking

Shrinkage of effect size (LFC estimates) is useful for visualization and ranking of genes. To shrink the LFC, we pass the dds object to the function lfcShrink. Below we specify to use the apeglm method for effect size shrinkage (Zhu, Ibrahim, and Love 2018), which improves on the previous estimator.

We provide the dds object and the name or number of the coefficient we want to shrink, where the number refers to the order of the coefficient as it appears in resultsNames(dds).

resultsNames(ddsDE)
## [1] "Intercept"                       "genotype_ch1_WEAK_vs_RX3"       
## [3] "genotype_ch1_WT_vs_RX3"          "zeitgeber_time_ch1_ZT09_vs_ZT03"
## [5] "zeitgeber_time_ch1_ZT15_vs_ZT03" "zeitgeber_time_ch1_ZT21_vs_ZT03"
## [1] "Intercept"                      "condition_treated_vs_untreated"

resLFC <- lfcShrink(ddsDE, coef="genotype_ch1_WT_vs_RX3", type="apeglm")

MA Plots

In DESeq2, the function plotMA shows the log2 fold changes attributable to a given variable over the mean of normalized counts for all the samples in the DESeqDataSet. Points will be colored red if the adjusted p value is less than 0.1. Points which fall out of the window are plotted as open triangles pointing either up or down.

DESeq2::plotMA(ddsDE, ylim = c(-2, 2))

It is more useful visualize the MA-plot for the shrunken log2 fold changes, which remove the noise associated with log2 fold changes from low count genes without requiring arbitrary filtering thresholds.

plotMA(resLFC, ylim=c(-2,2))

Principal Component Analysis

Provides information on how the samples are different

ddsDE_rlog <- ddsDE %>%
  rlogTransformation() 

ddsDE_rlog %>%
  DESeq2::plotPCA(intgroup = c("genotype_ch1", "zeitgeber_time_ch1")) +
  geom_vline(xintercept = 0, linetype = "dashed", colour = "red") +
  geom_hline(yintercept = 0, linetype = "dashed", colour = "red")

Conclusion There is a clear effect of genotype and zeitgeber on the differences in gene-expression, considering the point are distributed away from the centerpoint where PC1 = 0 and PC2 = 0 (crosshair dotted red lines)

Heatmaps

To learn more on the gene expression differences, a heatmap can be very effective to communicate the results.

library(pheatmap)
matrix_results <- assay(ddsDE_rlog)

ind <- matrix_results %>%
  rowMeans() %>%
  order(decreasing = TRUE) ## only the first 30 genes

top30 <- matrix_results[ind[1:30],]

heatmap <- pheatmap(top30,
                    scale = "row",
                    annotation_col = as.data.frame(
                      colData(ddsDE_rlog)[, c("genotype_ch1",
                                              "zeitgeber_time_ch1")]
                    ))
heatmap

Annotated heatmap

As a final step we will create an annotated version of the heatmap. Above we have the heatmap displaying the top 30 differentially regeulated genes with their respective ENSEMBL Zebrafish ids. To better understand the biological significance we would prefer to have gene names in stead. There are many way to get annotations for these genes. We alreday know one way: using a {biomaRt} query.

We will have to use the specific Zebrafish dataset to get the right annotations for the zebrafish ENSEMBL ids. The Latin name for zebrafish is Danio rerio or D. rerio in short.

library(biomaRt)
## all available marts
listMarts()
##                biomart                version
## 1 ENSEMBL_MART_ENSEMBL      Ensembl Genes 100
## 2   ENSEMBL_MART_MOUSE      Mouse strains 100
## 3     ENSEMBL_MART_SNP  Ensembl Variation 100
## 4 ENSEMBL_MART_FUNCGEN Ensembl Regulation 100
## using a mart
mart <- biomaRt::useMart('ensembl')

## get all available datasets
datasets <- listDatasets(mart) %>% 
  as_tibble()

## index for matching row that contain "Zebrafish" or "zebrafish"
ind <- str_detect(string = datasets$description, pattern = "(Z|z)ebrafish")

## get records
danio <- datasets[ind,]

## use the right mart
mart <- biomaRt::useMart('ensembl', dataset = danio$dataset)

attributes <- listAttributes(mart = mart) %>% as_tibble()

## search for gene_name or symbol
ind_attrib <- str_detect(
  string = attributes$name,
  pattern = "(gene_name|symbol)"
)

attributes[ind_attrib,]
